=20=20=20=20=20=20=20
<p class=3D"question" style=3D"margin-top: 1.5em; margin-bottom: 0px; color=
: #222; font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.4em; font-size: 1.1em; text-shado=
w: 0px 0px 2px #fff;">Back in 2010 when you did the first Rails Tutorial, d=
id you think it=E2=80=99d be popular a decade on?</p>
<p style=3D"margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0.8em;">I certainly hoped so. I c=
ould tell from its design and momentum that Rails had a good chance of bein=
g a relevant technology for many years to come. And the Web certainly wasn=
=E2=80=99t going anywhere!</p>

<p class=3D"question" style=3D"margin-top: 1.5em; margin-bottom: 0px; color=
: #222; font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.4em; font-size: 1.1em; text-shado=
w: 0px 0px 2px #fff;">What accounts for its staying power?</p>
<p style=3D"margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0.8em;">It owes a lot to the stay=
ing power of Rails itself. Rails creator David Heinemeier Hansson and the o=
ther core Rails developers have done a great job of keeping Rails relevant =
in a changing web development landscape.</p>

<p style=3D"margin-top: 0.8em; margin-bottom: 0.8em;">As for the Rails Tuto=
rial specifically, it has helped to have the support of the Rails community=
, which has made the Rails Tutorial=C2=A0(along with its parent company, Le=
arn Enough) a viable business. The financial support of Rails Tutorial cust=
omers has made it possible to continue updating the tutorial as Rails has e=
volved and grown.</p>
=20=20=20=20
<p class=3D"question" style=3D"margin-top: 1.5em; margin-bottom: 0px; color=
: #222; font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.4em; font-size: 1.1em; text-shado=
w: 0px 0px 2px #fff;">What most excites you about Ruby=E2=80=99s and/or Rai=
ls=E2=80=99 future?</p>
<p style=3D"margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0.8em;">
Ruby has a beauty and malleability that set it apart from competitors like =
Python and JavaScript. With Ruby-based companies like Stripe and Square sup=
porting it, I expect Ruby to continue to thrive.</p>

<p style=3D"margin-top: 0.8em; margin-bottom: 0.8em;">Rails, meanwhile, pow=
ers some of the biggest and most technologically savvy sites on the Web. Di=
d you know that, in the run-up to Rails 6, both GitHub and Shopify ran thei=
r production sites off of the latest development version of Rails? That=E2=
=80=99s the kind of battle-testing that hardly any other frameworks can mat=
ch.</p>
=20=20=20=20
<p class=3D"question" style=3D"margin-top: 1.5em; margin-bottom: 0px; color=
: #222; font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.4em; font-size: 1.1em; text-shado=
w: 0px 0px 2px #fff;">You claim to be a philosopher. How do you use that in=
 your everyday Ruby/development work?</p>
<p style=3D"margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0.8em;">I assume you=E2=80=99re r=
eferring to the inclusion of =E2=80=9Cnatural philosophy=E2=80=9D in my Twi=
tter bio. That term is an old-timey phrase that roughly means =E2=80=9Cscie=
nce=E2=80=9D, but it suggests a more integrated and even =E2=80=9Cspiritual=
=E2=80=9D approach to its subject. It emphasizes that science very much bel=
ongs as part of the =E2=80=9Cliberal arts=E2=80=9D. That=E2=80=99s the view=
